1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. dxc5 Nc6 5. Bb5 e6 6. Be3 Nge7 7. c3 Bd7 {
The most played move, obliging White to give up the bishop-pair. The threat is
...Nxe5, which holds good even if White defends the pawn with, say, Nf3.} ({
It might appear tempting to complete kingside development and castle as soon
as possible, but after a continuation like} 7... Nf5 8. Bd4 Be7 {it transpires,
unsurprisingly, that White will be able to keep all his material.} 9. Nf3 O-O
10. O-O Bd7 11. a4 Qc7 12. Nbd2 {and the window of time for Black to regain
the pawn has lapsed, leaving ...b6 as more or less the only option, after
which he faces a struggle for compensation. Despite this, I believe it is very
tricky for White to prove his edge following} b6 13. cxb6 axb6 $14) 8. Bxc6
Nxc6 9. f4 Qc7 (9... g5 $5 {was very common a decade or two ago, with such
players as Lutz employing it.} 10. Nf3 (10. fxg5 Nxe5 11. Nf3 $1 $14 {is a
modern engine solution, the point being that even if Black can gain back the
second pawn and retain the bishop-pair, the threats against f7 will take shape
sooner or later.}) 10... gxf4 11. Bxf4 Bxc5 12. Nbd2 Qb6 $40 {David,A-Khenkin,
I Geneve 1996}) 10. Nf3 Na5 11. b4 {Consistent, but as an earlier note showed,
Black usually gets reasonable play for the pawn even if White's bishop pair is
still on the board.} (11. Nbd2 Bxc5 12. Bxc5 Qxc5 13. Nd4 $11 {is a normal "1.
e4 player" response, hoping to be better in the resulting French structure by
virtue of having the d4-square. However, in this precise instance Black can
create co-ordination problems by means of a precise move-order:} Qb6 $1 (13...
O-O 14. N2b3 Nxb3 15. axb3 a5 16. O-O $14) 14. Rb1 Bb5 $1 {preventing castling
and creating enough counterplay to hold the balance. Nevertheless, I still
think Nbd2 is a more 'human' choice.}) 11... Nc4 12. Bd4 b6 13. cxb6 axb6 14.
O-O Be7 15. Nfd2 {Exchanging this knight expresses a wish to push the a-pawn
relatively directly.} (15. Nbd2 {is reasonable, hoping to exchange pieces and
ultimately push through in the centre, but White can't be better here either.
For instance,} Na3 $5 (15... Nxd2 16. Qxd2 O-O 17. a3 Ra6 18. Ne1 Rfa8 19. Nc2
Ba4 $44) 16. f5 Ba4 $1 (16... exf5 17. e6 fxe6 18. Bxg7 Rg8 19. Be5 $14 {
gives White a hugely annoying positional bind, if not yet an advantage
according to the machines.}) 17. Qe1 exf5 18. e6 f6 $1 $13) (15. f5 $6 exf5 16.
e6 fxe6 17. Bxg7 {is some way off being useful, because Black still controls
the e5-square.}) 15... O-O $6 {A little too slow.} (15... Nxd2 16. Qxd2 O-O $44
) 16. Nxc4 dxc4 $6 (16... Qxc4 17. Nd2 Qc6 18. a4 $14 {also sees White get off
the ground.}) 17. Nd2 $1 (17. a4 $14 {is natural too, but lets Black get a
bishop to d5.}) 17... Rfd8 18. Qe2 $6 {Now White won't be able to easily play
a4.} (18. a4 $16 {was again a strong freeing move.}) 18... b5 19. Ne4 (19. a4
Rxa4 20. Rxa4 bxa4 {is now not so great for White due to pins on the f1-a6
diagonal.}) 19... Bc6 {Positional constriction now fails White and he needs to
go for an attack before Black gets in ...Bd5, ...Qc6, ...Ra3, etc.} 20. f5 $6 {
Missing a little combination.} (20. Bc5 Bxe4 21. Bxe7 Qxe7 22. Qxe4 g6 $15 {
gives Black more than adequate compensation.}) (20. Nc5 Bd5 21. Rfd1 Ra3 22.
Qb2 Rda8 23. Rd2 h5 {and only Black can be better, but he isn't yet.}) 20...
exf5 21. Rxf5 $6 (21. Nd6 g6 $15) 21... Rxd4 $1 {The correct way to take
advantage of the overloading of the c3-pawn.} (21... Bxb4 $2 22. e6 $1 $18) 22.
cxd4 Qd7 23. Rff1 Qxd4+ 24. Nf2 Qd5 (24... Bxb4 25. Rad1 {and Black can't move
his queen with gain of tempo.}) 25. Nh3 Bxb4 $17 {Just like that, Black is
almost winning, and really should be putting his opponent away now. But
situations are usually hard to gauge when they involve fast-moving pawns as
compensation for material, and this was no exception.} 26. Ng5 (26. Nf4 Qe4 27.
Qxe4 Bxe4 $19 {is a truly thankless ending}) 26... Qd2 27. Qg4 {White
correctly avoids queen swaps, even if the engine thinks they were the way to
go.} h5 $1 28. Qg3 h4 (28... Qe2 $1 {is an engine finish. The f7-pawn takes
care of itself:} 29. Rxf7 $2 (29. Nxf7 Bc5+ 30. Kh1 Rxa2 $19) 29... Rxa2 $1 30.
Rxg7+ Kxg7 $19 {and White's discovered checks (and double check!) amount to
nothing.}) 29. Qg4 Be7 30. Nf3 (30. Nxf7 Qe3+ 31. Kh1 h3 $19) 30... Qd7 31.
Qxd7 {White has avoided it thus far, but against Black's excellent play, he
has no choice now except to trade queens.} (31. Qh5 g6 32. Qh6 Ra3 $19 {
is not the answer.}) 31... Bxd7 32. Rfd1 Bf5 33. Nd4 Bg4 34. Nxb5 Bxd1 35. Rxd1
Rxa2 36. Kf1 {I remember seeing this position on the board and thinking-
surely, White is toast now. But here, Black proceeded to blunder a pawn, and
with it, the lion's share of his advantage:} Bc5 $4 (36... Rb2 $19) 37. Rd8+
Kh7 38. Rc8 Be3 39. Rxc4 g5 (39... Rf2+ 40. Ke1 Rxg2 41. Rxh4+ Kg6 42. Re4 $1 {
no longer gives anything in particular- there is no way to regain the pawn
lead.}) 40. Re4 Bf4 $6 {Now the game ends quickly, and with disappointment for
Black.} (40... Ra1+ 41. Ke2 Bf4 $15 {was still something of a possibility, had
Black been in the right headspace to find it. White can't liquidate the
kingside pawns, and should instead play} 42. h3 (42. e6 $2 fxe6 43. Rxe6 Ra2+
44. Kf3 Bxh2 $17 {could still be hard to hold}) (42. g3 $4 Bxg3 $1 $19) 42...
Ra5 43. Nd6 Kg6 44. e6 $1 {White has to see this idea to get the minor pieces
off the board, otherwise the endgame could still be hard.} Bxd6 45. e7 Bxe7 46.
Rxe7 $15 {is a standard 3v2}) 41. g3 hxg3 42. hxg3 Bxg3 43. e6 fxe6 44. Rxe6 {
Very disappointing for Julio Granda, but a good fightback from Jakovenko
following a lacklustre early middlegame.} 1/2-1/2

