and his second-closest chaser, even if superficially the game was a little
boring!} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bg5 h6 {
Probably better than ...0-0, because it gives Black options to play with or
without ...c5 and have logical play in either case.} (6... O-O 7. e3 c5 8. dxc5
Nbd7 {is another topical continuation, but as in so many variations these days,
the IQP can serve to decide an otherwise basically level situation, purely
because it demands more resourcefulness from the "defender".} (8... h6 9. Bxf6
Qxf6 10. Rc1 $14 {-remember this point!}) 9. Rc1 Qa5 (9... Nxc5 10. Qd4 $1) 10.
a3 {Great exchange sacrifice, which has been known for some time.} Bxc3+ 11.
Rxc3 Ne4 12. b4 Nxc3 13. Qa1 Qa4 14. Qxc3 a5 15. b5 {Black's second problem,
after his IQP, is the fact that his queen is virtually trapped. It is highly
susceptible to ideas like b6+Bb5.} Nxc5 (15... Re8 16. Nd4 Nxc5 17. Qxc5 Bg4 {
is the computer's suggested interpretation, but no doubt the top guys have an
answer here too.}) 16. Qxc5 Bf5 (16... Be6 17. Qc1 Rfc8 18. Qa1 Qc2 19. Be2 $16
{was a predecessor game and the main reason for including this note: Topalov,
V-Carlsen,M Wijk aan Zee 2007}) 17. Qc3 Rfc8 18. Qa1 Qc2 19. Nd4 {White is
close to winning, but the elite rapid game from this position is worth quoting
in its entirety.} Qc1+ 20. Qxc1 Rxc1+ 21. Kd2 Rac8 22. Nxf5 R8c2+ 23. Kd3 Rxf2
24. Ne7+ (24. Ng3 $1 $18) 24... Kh8 25. g3 Ra1 (25... Rcxf1 26. Rxf1 Rxf1 27.
Kc2 $16 {is also winning in the long run}) 26. Kd4 Rc1 27. Bg2 $1 {Well
calculated.} Rd2+ 28. Ke5 f6+ 29. Kd6 Rc3 30. Rf1 h6 31. Rxf6 hxg5 32. Rf8+ Kh7
33. Bh3 g4 34. Bxg4 Rxe3 35. Bf5+ g6 36. Bxg6+ Kg7 37. Rg8+ {Aronian,
L-Nakamura,H Leuven 2016}) 7. Bh4 O-O 8. e3 Bf5 $1 {Most solid and best. I
believe Black could be worse after ...c5.} (8... c5 {is also played. Now
people tend not to take because unlike the version without ...h6, Bh4- there
